<br>
I was listening to the radio the other day (mind you Australia is a very passive country and want really no part of this war) and an Iraqian caller called in. He left Iraq in 1991. He still has family in Baghdad.  When the radio host asked him what he thought of this war, if he was happy about it. The man paused for about 30seconds and I felt like he was trying to choose his words carefully. He said I dont like war but with this man and his government I really see no choice.  The host said this war could cost your family their lives and the man understood. He said for the greater good of the people of Iraq, he would gladly sacrific some of his family to get that man out. He told about some of the things that Hussein has done and it made me very sad.  The man also said that for Iraqians this is not an invasion ... this is a liberation. To me this really hit home.  Also he said that he lost contact with his family on Monday (US Sunday night). The phone lines had gone dead. The host said that he promised to call this man back in a few days to get his perspective again.<br>
<br>
I am sad that the UN isnt back what seems an obvious war to me.  I see the same link to Milosevic that Rayvenn sees. My hubby's family is Croatian-as you can see from my blinkie.<br>
